00:35.906 --> 00:39.131
who jumped in and were tremendously helpful.

00:39.371 --> 00:43.977
These are two servants of the church who made that possible.

00:44.057 --> 00:44.939
So thank you, thank you.

00:46.100 --> 00:50.206
As we get started here, today's sermon is about Pharisees.

00:50.967 --> 00:53.451
And I asked my son on the way to church today.

00:53.471 --> 01:00.661
I was like, do you think it'd be weird if I just like asked the congregation to jump in and like and answer a question.

01:00.721 --> 01:02.563
And he said, Dad, you do you.

01:02.864 --> 01:04.466
And I said, okay.

01:04.578 --> 01:05.299
I think I will.

01:07.262 --> 01:13.831
So you tell me, I actually thought about forcing all of you people in the back row to come on up here.

01:14.813 --> 01:15.874
One of these days I will.

01:17.476 --> 01:20.340
You tell me one word, two words, three words max.

01:21.282 --> 01:22.904
What makes a Pharisee a Pharisee?

01:27.050 --> 01:27.511
Legalism.

01:31.396 --> 01:32.658
Self-righteous.

01:35.042 --> 01:36.444
holier than now.

01:42.550 --> 01:43.531
Closed-minded.

01:48.937 --> 01:49.237
Loud?

01:50.899 --> 01:51.420
Say louder.

01:53.041 --> 01:53.542
Be a Pharisee.

01:54.403 --> 01:57.126
Anybody else before we jump in here?

02:01.510 --> 02:02.171
I like that one.

02:02.531 --> 02:04.914
Lack of self-reflection.

02:05.282 --> 02:05.943
What did you say?

02:05.963 --> 02:09.709
That's true.

02:09.729 --> 02:10.130
You cheated.

02:12.774 --> 02:13.435
It was loud.

02:15.799 --> 02:16.200
All right.

02:16.640 --> 02:22.290
I had here just kind of off, you know, just a few judgmental, hypocritical.

02:23.231 --> 02:27.538
There's certain that the right prideful is a big one.

02:27.906 --> 02:49.127
But maybe what you didn't say and where I need us to go first before we can then get back to that other side is to recognize a few things you might not expect to say about Pharisees, which is that many of them like try to be good, good people.

02:49.287 --> 02:50.549
They try to be good people.

02:51.870 --> 02:55.954
They do a lot for their synagogues or church.

02:56.930 --> 03:01.095
They take their faith very seriously, very seriously.

03:02.037 --> 03:07.684
They memorize scripture and they know it better than you probably know your scripture, to be honest with you.

03:09.086 --> 03:19.900
They use their scripture regularly and they strive to read it very closely and keep every letter of the law because they're serious about it.

03:21.101 --> 03:24.626
They are tithers, they pray,

03:25.666 --> 03:26.867
They even fast.

03:27.488 --> 03:28.389
Do you do that, right?

03:28.730 --> 03:35.298
And so maybe what I'd say is if this describes you, there's a chance you might be a Pharisee.

03:38.162 --> 03:41.185
One last question before we pray and get started.

03:41.245 --> 03:46.412
Who is Jesus more likely to enjoy the company of?

03:47.293 --> 03:51.378
The Pharisees or the sinners?

03:53.026 --> 03:54.448
Pharisees or the sinners?

03:55.028 --> 04:00.034
Who do you find him with and enjoying the company of more often?

04:02.256 --> 04:03.558
The sinners, right?

04:04.319 --> 04:05.540
I think that's undisputed.

04:05.560 --> 04:21.458
Maybe someone wants to dispute that, but I think it's undisputed that Jesus is spending the majority of his time, at least the times where he's laughing and having a good time, not with the church people, but with the sinners.

04:22.530 --> 04:34.063
And I think that's worthy of your reflection, mind too, like why of all people who comes, Jesus comes and spends time with them.

04:36.586 --> 04:41.532
All right, before we get into the sermon itself, we should probably pray.

04:41.572 --> 04:43.214
It's gonna be an interesting one.

04:46.357 --> 04:47.058
Father in heaven.

04:49.890 --> 04:58.759
Lord, each of us has a heart that is exposed to you right now, whether we realize it or not.

05:01.722 --> 05:06.007
You can see right down to the smallest parts of who we are.

05:07.648 --> 05:16.818
And God, some of us come this morning with some heart hearts, impenetrable hearts, hearts of Pharisees.

05:18.562 --> 05:20.084
This is what we're worried about today.

05:21.065 --> 05:22.466
This is what we're talking about today.

05:23.788 --> 05:27.552
And so God, shine your light on those places.

05:28.934 --> 05:36.122
Show us, each of us, where we are the Pharisee, that we might repent and change our ways.

05:36.943 --> 05:38.344
In Christ's name we pray, amen.

05:41.508 --> 05:46.994
We are, as I talked about last week, in some ways like we're going through

05:47.074 --> 05:50.959
Well, we are going through the soils of the parable of the sower.

05:51.000 --> 05:52.562
I'm not gonna go over the parable again.

05:52.622 --> 05:57.268
But if you recall, it has four soils to it, right?

05:57.308 --> 06:05.921
It has the path which is compacted and the seed falls onto it and then the birds just come and they eat it up, right?

06:06.061 --> 06:09.846
It's just like, it can't penetrate into the ground.

06:09.906 --> 06:11.909
And then there's the rocky soil, remember?

06:12.229 --> 06:15.474
And the roots start down in the soil

06:15.682 --> 06:17.887
But then it just can't go that deep.

06:18.348 --> 06:22.216
And eventually the sun scorches it up and it goes away.

06:22.356 --> 06:32.438
And then there's the thorny situation, which may not be the soil itself, but it's like the environment around the soil.

06:32.518 --> 06:36.466
And so the plant starts to grow up, but it can't get the

06:36.738 --> 07:01.266
breath it needs and it can't grow like it should because it gets choked out and so it doesn't produce the fruit that it should and then the last soil is the the good soil and this is the one that produces fruit in abundance and it has 30 times, 60 times, 100 times what you might expect it to produce right and and of course we're going for good soil but over these

07:01.762 --> 07:10.274
I kind of want to take a look at each of these and then pinpoint what they look like in real life, in your life and in my life.

07:10.914 --> 07:17.263
And my guess is each of us has a little bit of each of these soils inside of us.

07:17.984 --> 07:22.150
And so it's not like you can say, oh, well, this is this guy's problem.

07:22.170 --> 07:23.652
And that's her problem.

07:24.873 --> 07:28.338
No, every one of us needs to do some of this inner work.

07:28.546 --> 07:34.414
And then of course, the theme of the year is all of this leads to transformation, right?

07:34.994 --> 07:46.669
And so as we do some of this inner work today, we are looking at what has to be the most dangerous problem that I think I see in all of the New Testament, and that is this hard soil.

07:47.390 --> 07:56.562
And I do believe that as Jesus is telling this parable and that as he's talking to the crowds, he has in mind the Pharisees.

07:57.026 --> 08:14.550
the religious elites of his day, the people who attend church regularly and do all the right church things, and yet somehow the seed, the word, it doesn't penetrate, it doesn't start to even grow roots, it goes nowhere.

08:14.570 --> 08:26.866
As I was sitting prepping for this sermon, I was trying to figure out like, all right, what do I name this sermon?

08:27.042 --> 08:38.316
I was imagining not only like compacted soil, but like it's coming over it and like paving over it with a thick, you know, bit of asphalt, right?

08:38.396 --> 08:45.805
Like, and as I'm sitting there thinking like, man, some people's hearts, they're not just compacted down.

08:46.586 --> 08:47.767
They're paved over.

08:48.548 --> 08:51.031
And this is a desperate situation, right?

08:51.832 --> 08:53.394
And I what should I call this sermon?

08:54.146 --> 08:57.030
And then I don't know why, but the song just popped in my head.

08:57.090 --> 08:57.811
You know this song?

08:58.552 --> 08:59.333
They pay for it.

08:59.374 --> 09:00.615
You know, don't make me sing it.

09:01.276 --> 09:05.282
This is Joni Mitchell, the big yellow taxi.

09:05.943 --> 09:07.806
Some of you younger people may not know this.

09:07.926 --> 09:09.088
Yeah, you're shaking your heads no.

09:09.688 --> 09:11.371
That's fine, understandable.

09:11.711 --> 09:15.216
And then after hers, Amy Grant, right, sings a version of this.

09:15.637 --> 09:17.900
The counting crows come along and sing this.

09:17.920 --> 09:19.823
Are we all on the same page here?

09:21.345 --> 09:21.906
Okay.

09:23.106 --> 09:32.141
They paved paradise and put up a parking lot with a pink hotel, a boutique, and a swinging hotspot.

09:34.305 --> 09:36.068
Don't it always seem to go?

09:38.272 --> 09:40.496
You don't know what you got till it's gone.

09:40.516 --> 09:40.756
What?

09:42.319 --> 09:45.043
They paved paradise and put up a parking lot.

09:47.728 --> 09:47.948
Right?

09:48.048 --> 09:49.010
You know the song, right?

09:49.250 --> 09:52.814
OK, the song is not really about hard hearts.

09:52.855 --> 10:05.370
And yet, in some ways, the pastor, preacher in me loves to turn something into something here.

10:05.531 --> 10:14.642
And so as the song is like playing in my head, I'm thinking about the nature of our hearts and what God's trying to do in there.

10:15.682 --> 10:18.266
And it's supposed to be a paradise.

10:18.606 --> 10:22.932
It's supposed to be this thing that grows in abundance.

10:23.773 --> 10:30.202
It's supposed to be maybe even like an Eden kind of paradise where there's Shalom or peace.

10:30.823 --> 10:33.767
There's like unity with God happening in there.

10:34.548 --> 10:39.434
There's like an abundance that you then feed other people with.

10:39.875 --> 10:41.337
It's this kind of paradise.

10:42.118 --> 10:45.042
And the Pharisees and God forbid you and I

10:45.570 --> 10:46.952
We pave over that.

10:51.919 --> 10:53.762
Our passage today, we already read it.

10:53.782 --> 10:56.065
I want to read it again.

10:56.126 --> 10:58.108
So we'll go ahead and show it up here.

10:58.229 --> 11:01.714
If you want to turn there, it's Luke 18, 9 to 14.

11:01.834 --> 11:04.197
We're actually going to end up looking at a few passages.

11:05.039 --> 11:09.726
And truth be told, I was kind of so into this.

11:09.846 --> 11:15.474
I thought we could do a lot of things about how not to be a Pharisee.

11:15.682 --> 11:25.634
Right, because there are so many interactions where Jesus bumps into these people and he keeps having trouble with the Pharisees, right?

11:25.674 --> 11:27.356
And why?

11:27.436 --> 11:29.899
Like why are they so unreceptive?

11:30.560 --> 11:35.486
And then how can we make sure that we are not like this?

11:36.086 --> 11:42.514
So let's start with Luke 18, nine to 14 and we'll read it together and we'll see right up front

11:42.978 --> 11:45.842
one of the main problems that's happening.

11:46.944 --> 11:57.278
So Jesus tells this parable to some who trusted in themselves that they were righteous and they treated others with contempt.

11:57.559 --> 12:00.563
You see that just the first verse, we've already got two big problems.

12:01.664 --> 12:02.205
What are they?

12:02.245 --> 12:07.693
Self-righteous, which that came up in our diagnosis of the Pharisees.

12:08.454 --> 12:11.218
And then what's the other one, contempt, right?

12:11.874 --> 12:13.456
Maybe it's like a judgmentalism.

12:14.197 --> 12:16.841
They're looking at other people contemptuously.

12:16.861 --> 12:27.517
Interestingly, if you were here yesterday for the marriage workshop, there's four horsemen of the apocalypse, apparently, in your relationships.

12:28.077 --> 12:32.023
And the worst of them, the worst of them, is contempt.

12:32.984 --> 12:37.711
And if you hold contempt for your spouse, good luck in marriage.

12:38.292 --> 12:39.634
Well, it's not all that different.

12:40.386 --> 12:41.628
with other relationships.

12:42.710 --> 12:44.292
And so the Pharisees, what do they do?

12:44.332 --> 12:48.759
They look at other people and they hold contempt for them.

12:49.960 --> 12:56.951
And so you've got to ask yourself, if you're experiencing some of that in your life, again, you might be a Pharisee.

12:59.575 --> 13:09.490
So he tells the parable, verse 10, two men went to the temple to pray, one's a Pharisee and the other's the tax collector, the sinner.

13:10.146 --> 13:20.758
The Pharisee standing by himself prayed thus, God, I thank you that I am not like other men.

13:20.818 --> 13:33.152
You know, those extortioners, the unjust, those adulterers, or even that guy over there, the tax collector.

13:35.394 --> 13:38.578
I lie fast twice a week.

13:39.170 --> 13:42.954
And I give tithes of all that I get.

13:45.076 --> 13:51.642
But then in the other corners, tax collector standing far off, he wouldn't even lift his eyes to heaven.

13:52.502 --> 13:59.909
Instead, he beat his breasts, he's crying out, and he's saying, God, be merciful to me.

14:00.910 --> 14:03.533
I know that I'm a sinner.

14:04.894 --> 14:09.138
I tell you this man went down to his house justified

14:09.378 --> 14:14.265
He was actually made righteous by God rather than the Pharisee.

14:14.646 --> 14:25.542
For everyone who exalts himself will be humbled, but the one who humbleds himself will be exalted.

14:28.106 --> 14:29.989
So what words describe the Pharisee here?

14:30.029 --> 14:39.122
Pride, judgmentalism, he is contemptuous, he is self-righteous.

14:39.746 --> 14:43.473
But let me suggest one more thing that he also is.

14:44.595 --> 14:45.376
He's ignorant.

14:46.879 --> 14:47.520
He's ignorant.

14:47.681 --> 14:49.284
He doesn't know it, right?

14:49.885 --> 14:58.601
He doesn't know that he's walking away from this scene, not made righteous and yet needs to be.

14:58.641 --> 15:03.570
The tax collector, of course, he is made righteous.

15:04.034 --> 15:05.256
And it's because he knows it.

15:05.356 --> 15:06.478
He knows he needs it.

15:06.538 --> 15:07.580
And so he's doing what?

15:07.861 --> 15:09.123
He's doing that inner work.

15:09.143 --> 15:13.871
He's looking inside and he's saying, I am a messed up human being.

15:14.051 --> 15:18.278
I have sinned before God and God have mercy on me.

15:18.779 --> 15:19.741
I need you.

15:19.781 --> 15:27.474
The tax collector doesn't seem to need God and instead is able to perhaps even play God.

15:27.650 --> 15:33.057
and say, this person needs God, the adult are over here, and this tax collector, he definitely needs God.

15:33.277 --> 15:37.082
The extortioner over here definitely needs mercy, right?

15:37.523 --> 15:39.546
But me, I think I'm all right.

15:40.467 --> 15:42.129
I think I'm doing just fine.

15:45.994 --> 15:47.236
Skip to another passage.

15:47.736 --> 15:49.098
If you want to turn there, you're welcome to.

15:49.138 --> 15:50.941
This one's from Mark chapter three.

15:51.001 --> 15:52.883
I don't have them up on the board here.

15:53.003 --> 15:55.026
Mark chapter three, one to six.

15:55.394 --> 16:01.825
This is a passage that you might be familiar with where a man with a withered hand, right?

16:02.446 --> 16:04.589
He's not able to use one of his hands.

16:05.010 --> 16:10.759
He's in the synagogue on a Sunday or a Sabbath, Saturday, actually, for them.

16:10.819 --> 16:12.482
But it's the Sabbath.

16:12.642 --> 16:14.846
And you know, you're not supposed to work on the Sabbath.

16:14.926 --> 16:17.711
And so Jesus goes in and what does he do?

16:17.771 --> 16:19.273
He heals him.

16:20.355 --> 16:22.098
And how do the Pharisees respond?

16:23.330 --> 16:24.692
I say, shame, shame, shame.

16:26.094 --> 16:27.256
You're working on the Sabbath.

16:27.316 --> 16:28.799
You're breaking the law.

16:28.819 --> 16:33.126
The law clearly says you are not supposed to do work on the Sabbath.

16:33.166 --> 16:35.990
And now Jesus, look, you've done this terrible thing.

16:37.513 --> 16:42.260
Jesus' response, I think, is wonderful here.

16:42.681 --> 16:48.370
It's this really nice window into Jesus' inner life.

16:48.994 --> 16:53.319
If at some point you wanna look at it, it's in verse five, I'll just read this part.

16:53.339 --> 17:02.731
He says, Jesus looked around at them, and here he's looking at the Pharisees, and he looks at them with anger.

17:02.791 --> 17:04.514
Anger.

17:05.895 --> 17:07.858
Now it takes a lot to get Jesus angry.

17:08.959 --> 17:13.265
But who are the people he's normally angry with when you see him angry in the gospels?

17:13.285 --> 17:17.490
100% of the time, it's the religious folks.

17:18.306 --> 17:21.710
He doesn't really get angry at the sinners out there.

17:22.450 --> 17:23.492
He has mercy on them.

17:23.532 --> 17:25.233
He has compassion for them.

17:26.074 --> 17:27.416
He wants to save them.

17:27.476 --> 17:30.019
He's reaching out to help them.

17:31.620 --> 17:34.964
But the Pharisees, that's a different story.

17:36.045 --> 17:43.994
So he is angered with them and he grieves at there, and here's our phrase, hardness of heart.

17:44.975 --> 17:48.018
He's grieving at their hardness of heart.

17:50.306 --> 18:15.810
So if your Christianity causes you to wonder if the healing of the world somehow bumps up against your version of the way the world should work or the way you read your scripture and you're not sure if you should help out in a certain situation because it goes against your moral compass, we'll say.

18:17.211 --> 18:19.954
You might find yourself in this passage

18:20.898 --> 18:24.283
in this Mark III Pharisee passage.

18:25.544 --> 18:38.382
Just to give you a real world example here, a few years ago, we did a thing here at South Run with some other folks in the area called Raft, resettling Afghans together.

18:39.343 --> 18:50.258
And one of the concerns was, well, these Afghan families who are coming from Afghanistan and they're fleeing the Taliban, and they're coming here with nothing.

18:50.370 --> 18:51.191
in their pockets.

18:51.271 --> 18:55.617
They're literally leaving everything behind, but they're Muslim, right?

18:56.077 --> 18:57.819
So, I mean, should we help them?

18:58.300 --> 19:05.089
Is that something we should really do or that might actually bump up against our moral compass of what we Christian?

19:05.710 --> 19:18.706
Well, if that's your attitude and if that's your thought process, then I assure you, you're closer to the Pharisees of Mark three than you are to the Jesus of Mark three.

19:21.826 --> 19:26.733
skipping to another passage, John 9, 13 to 34.

19:26.773 --> 19:28.656
You can read it of your own core.

19:28.716 --> 19:35.987
This is a lengthy story about a man who was born blind and the Pharisees are trying to figure out what's going on here.

19:36.027 --> 19:38.391
Who sinned?

19:39.092 --> 19:40.574
Was it this guy who sinned?

19:40.594 --> 19:42.958
Was it his parents sinned?

19:44.300 --> 19:47.404
And then Jesus is like, no, it doesn't work like that.

19:47.565 --> 19:49.407
And then he heals him, right?

19:49.948 --> 19:51.250
And then he heals the blind man.

19:52.002 --> 20:00.831
And then the next question is, well, we know this Jesus guy and we know that it's the Sabbath that he's doing this on.

20:00.911 --> 20:03.914
So surely this is not of God.

20:05.956 --> 20:07.898
Like God wouldn't do it this way.

20:08.318 --> 20:12.262
God wouldn't use a man like this and he wouldn't do it on the Sabbath.

20:12.802 --> 20:15.805
And so we know that something's not right here.

20:15.845 --> 20:20.690
That's the way the Pharisee thinks.

20:21.282 --> 20:28.490
And here again, it's their biblicism bumping up against what's really happening in the world.

20:29.771 --> 20:36.899
And they're saying to themselves, well, I know the God of the Bible, the one I read in the Bible anyway, and God wouldn't do this.

20:41.845 --> 20:45.569
Turns out I think some of us do this on occasion as well.

20:46.610 --> 20:50.514
We have these small preconceived notions

20:50.658 --> 20:53.362
of where God is at work in the world.

20:53.422 --> 21:00.712
And then when God works in other ways, we must think, well, that's clearly not God because God wouldn't do that.

21:00.732 --> 21:09.544
Those people are either not deserving of it, maybe they're the wrong person or maybe it's the wrong institution or it's the wrong church or the wrong denomination or whatever it might be.

21:09.564 --> 21:16.434
I would encourage you to think to yourself, well, maybe that's the way a Pharisee might think.

21:17.634 --> 21:22.866
And to give you a real world example of this, I was surprised.

21:24.329 --> 21:33.330
A number of three years ago, 2023, my school, as very college, where I went to college, had a revival.

21:34.018 --> 21:46.537
And it was this really powerful thing where thousands of people come from across the globe and show up, and everybody's testifying that there's an outpouring happening.

21:46.557 --> 21:48.240
And this is amazing, right?

21:49.061 --> 21:50.523
Maybe you heard of it, maybe not.

21:52.046 --> 22:02.802
And then I was a little surprised to see John MacArthur, well-respected pastor, questioning the veracity

22:03.010 --> 22:04.291
of the movement itself.

22:05.432 --> 22:05.933
And why?

22:06.053 --> 22:07.014
Why would he do this?

22:07.735 --> 22:09.516
He didn't doubt that something was happening.

22:10.277 --> 22:13.260
He just said, well, this is a Wesleyan or Minnie in school.

22:13.961 --> 22:20.587
And I don't know that the God of my small head is going to actually move there.

22:20.607 --> 22:22.629
And so what does he do?

22:22.829 --> 22:25.332
He says, well, I'm just not so sure that's real.

22:26.233 --> 22:28.315
God doesn't work that way.

22:28.335 --> 22:31.538
I would say,

22:32.194 --> 22:37.442
That is not John MacArthur's most Christian moment.

22:40.125 --> 23:00.114
Pharisees in their small world of certainty think they have the corner on the truth and so therefore need to shrink God down to their size and their expectations rather than letting God expand their minds and their hearts.

23:01.730 --> 23:07.001
that might be the easiest way to describe a Pharisee, small minds and small hearts.

23:09.446 --> 23:22.354
Matthew 23, 23 to 24, another example of how Pharisees think and how their hearts get hardened, because here Jesus is

23:22.690 --> 23:24.192
talking to some Pharisees.

23:24.272 --> 23:28.839
And if you've read Matthew 23, this is easily Jesus at his angriest.

23:28.919 --> 23:32.405
And it's a whole chapter filled with woe to you Pharisees.

23:32.765 --> 23:34.107
Look at what you're doing.

23:34.388 --> 23:38.013
You are whitewashed tombs is what he says.

23:38.073 --> 23:45.625
And he says, the whitewashed tombs, because out here, it looks white and bright and clean.

23:46.366 --> 23:51.794
But inside of that tomb, inside of your heart, is something rotting.

23:51.938 --> 23:52.619
and dead.

23:53.560 --> 23:53.840
This.

23:55.002 --> 23:59.948
This is what Pharisees looks like.

23:59.968 --> 24:05.535
It looks like it's all put together out here, but inside is something different.

24:05.555 --> 24:10.101
But in Matthew 23, 23, and 24, he's talking about the way that they tithe.

24:10.682 --> 24:13.926
And he says to them, you tithe your mint.

24:14.987 --> 24:16.809
Like, you know, if you've got a mint plant, right?

24:17.590 --> 24:18.772
You tithe your dill.

24:19.613 --> 24:20.434
Again,

24:20.706 --> 24:22.428
dill plants, right?

24:22.548 --> 24:24.470
You tie your herb garden.

24:25.211 --> 24:34.841
You're willing to take 10% out of that arrow grow that's sitting in your basement, and you're bringing that to the church, and you're doing the smallest thing, right?

24:34.981 --> 24:40.066
You're doing all the tithing, and he's saying, but you've forgotten the most important parts.

24:41.248 --> 24:47.474
You've forgotten justice and mercy and faithfulness is what he says.

24:49.186 --> 24:53.554
And if I could like recast this, we took tithes today.

24:53.615 --> 25:08.864
And when we tithe, the goal is that it changes your heart, that it's not staying out here somewhere, that it's actually penetrating inside and changing you into a different kind of person.

25:10.006 --> 25:11.890
A person who cares about justice and you

25:12.610 --> 25:22.545
in order to make justice a reality in the world, who cares about mercy, in order to make mercy happen in the world, who cares about faithfulness, right?

25:22.585 --> 25:26.030
That is what we're going for, changed hearts.

25:26.871 --> 25:29.234
It was very easy to give, just to give.

25:29.255 --> 25:34.222
I would remind you, Jesus continues and he says, keep tithing.

25:35.384 --> 25:36.265
Don't stop that part.

25:38.448 --> 25:39.630
But do the other part too.

25:40.551 --> 25:42.514
Let it change who

25:42.658 --> 25:43.219
You are.

25:44.661 --> 25:48.025
Last passage, Luke 7, 29 to 30.

25:49.707 --> 25:55.134
Jesus is talking again to a crowd of people, but the Pharisees are nearby.

25:55.154 --> 25:57.637
And he says the following.

25:58.198 --> 26:03.805
He says, when all the people heard this, what he was saying, the tax collectors are there too.

26:04.005 --> 26:06.508
Man, they make a real impression here.

26:07.810 --> 26:11.314
And they declared, God is just.

26:12.482 --> 26:22.677
God is making all things right through this person, Jesus, because they were baptized with the baptism of John, and they were bought into the whole system.

26:23.618 --> 26:35.855
But in verse 30, it goes on and it says, the Pharisees and the lawyers rejected the purposes of God for themselves.

26:37.778 --> 26:40.562
This might be the hardest line of all.

26:41.314 --> 26:48.183
because the truth is this, that God actually wants those Pharisees to come to Him.

26:48.945 --> 27:02.283
God wants those Pharisees to break the pavement of their hearts, to dust it up, and to plant bunches of seeds, and to become the people that He wants them to be, His designed them to be.

27:02.363 --> 27:10.354
But the Pharisees and the lawyers, they reject the purpose of God for themselves.

27:12.834 --> 27:21.326
So it turns out the Pharisee is the person, maybe you, maybe me, who has been to church your whole life.

27:22.508 --> 27:26.574
And outwardly, you've played the part of the Christian.

27:27.555 --> 27:28.456
You have tithed.

27:29.197 --> 27:30.920
You have come on Sunday mornings.

27:31.481 --> 27:33.423
You have read your Bible faithfully.

27:33.924 --> 27:35.286
You have prayed your prayers.

27:35.787 --> 27:38.130
You have a strong moral compass.

27:38.466 --> 27:42.571
You crave certainty and do not do well with ambiguity.

27:42.631 --> 27:55.106
You know who the sinners are and who the saints are, but despite all of the outer work that you've accomplished and can point to, an inner work has not occurred.

27:56.148 --> 28:01.414
Your heart is as hard as the day you were baptized, maybe harder.

28:02.555 --> 28:04.658
You know all the right theology

28:04.834 --> 28:07.457
You know who's in and who's out of the kingdom.

28:07.517 --> 28:15.546
You sit in judgment over others who need to get their act together rather than greet them with grace and mercy.

28:16.166 --> 28:22.513
You are kind to people's faces, but behind their backs you scheme and plot.

28:23.434 --> 28:30.482
You are concerned not only with your own righteousness, but in making sure everyone else knows you are righteous too.

28:31.170 --> 28:41.223
You trade a heart of justice and mercy and faithfulness for religion that talks about those things but does nothing about it.

28:42.064 --> 28:53.178
Rather than learning to love as Jesus loved, you have justified yourself and the contempt you feel toward others and you do so by quoting all the right scriptures.

28:57.063 --> 28:59.506
If that sounds harsh, it should.

29:01.058 --> 29:05.744
I will warn you of all the people Jesus meets in the gospels.

29:06.325 --> 29:18.561
He has the harshest words for the hardhearted, for the Pharisees, for those who refuse to allow the seeds to penetrate the soil.

29:20.043 --> 29:21.986
And so this is what hard soil looks like.

29:22.987 --> 29:28.434
And God's redeeming word seems to have no chance in this soil.

29:29.826 --> 29:31.428
because you don't need righteousness.

29:31.949 --> 29:32.951
You've got your own.

29:34.092 --> 29:37.457
And so the birds come and they eat those seeds right up.

29:38.759 --> 29:46.731
The wind sweeps them away and the seed never produces the fruit that was always intended to produce.

29:49.115 --> 29:51.178
You've paved over the paradise.

29:51.899 --> 29:52.700
That is your heart.

29:54.803 --> 29:55.925
So what's the antidote?

29:56.666 --> 29:57.427
It's very simple.

29:58.449 --> 29:59.250
Repentance.

30:00.514 --> 30:15.794
A recognition of your hard heart, asking God to break it, to show you your impenetrable ways, to take a sledgehammer to the paved over paradise that God is wanting to grow within you.

30:16.615 --> 30:18.557
I assure you, it is not too late.

30:19.919 --> 30:27.368
I encourage you to make a commitment today to live with the tenderness of heart that God is calling all of us toward.

30:28.229 --> 30:28.690
Let us pray.

30:44.034 --> 31:01.461
Jesus, I worry that in the same ways the Pharisees pushed away your hard words, that the very people who need to hear this hard word will push it away.

31:04.546 --> 31:12.498
But God, I would ask that in your mercy for that person, that you take the sledgehammer to their

31:14.498 --> 31:20.385
that you begin to do the hard work of tilling up that hard soil.

31:20.405 --> 31:26.893
God, as you do, it will be deeply uncomfortable.

31:26.913 --> 31:43.634
But on the other side of all that is a softness, a tenderness of heart, a soil that is capable of growing new life, new life that the Pharisee can't even imagine, new life

31:44.418 --> 31:45.239
It will feel right.

31:45.600 --> 31:47.602
It will feel like Shalom.

31:47.622 --> 31:50.406
It will feel like the Garden of Eden.

31:50.426 --> 31:52.349
It will be union with you.

31:53.390 --> 32:00.720
It will be the ability to feed the masses, the fruit that you are producing in that person.

32:00.740 --> 32:11.474
God, do not let us leave today without taking the magic to the parts of our heart, but a heart that needs to be broken.

32:13.026 --> 32:14.642
That's what Jesus told him.

